body.text:
In practice, what matters most is not “what we want to obtain”, but what we are willing to give up.

If a breeding program cannot answer the question “which outcomes will not be kept even if they appear”, it will eventually be driven by the market, probability, or wishful thinking.

I explicitly reject a path that uses any single visible trait as the primary engine of breeding. The reason is simple: in rodents—where generations turn over quickly and genetics express fast—any trait that is amplified in isolation will be paid for by sacrifices elsewhere. Without a clear priority order, those sacrifices often happen unconsciously.

Therefore, in real decisions I follow a one-way order of judgment:
First, assess whether temperament is stable, predictable, and compatible with long-term living;
second, assess whether health shows consistency across generations;
third, assess whether structure supports long-term movement and physical load;
and only then consider appearance and other phenotypes.

Temperament problems, once introduced into a breeding program, are almost impossible to fully eliminate later. Health problems often emerge with delay. Structural issues magnify over time. And appearance issues are simply appearance issues.

I deliberately avoid keeping individuals that are “good in most ways, but have a bit of a temperament problem” for breeding—because in experience, that “bit of a problem” often amplifies into systemic risk in the next generations.
